                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Okay,
<br />

<br />
First, I appologise, but after thinking abou this for a while, I realized placing this anywere other than the /rants section would be wrong, as ultimately this will be viewed as a rant.
<br />

<br />
I've asked this question in a few different forms of the last few months, but I wanted to restate it, this time with a bit more background.
<br />

<br />
Below is the cut and pasted text from SoE regarding what an enchanter is:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Enchanter 
<br />
Enchanters are the most subtle of spell casters, with little focus on doing damage directly but tremendous impact on the world around them. Enchanters are primarily a magic-using class, with the ability to wear cloth armor and wield blunt weapons and daggers. 
<br />

<br />
Enchanters specialize on improving the minds of their allies, with unmatched mana regeneration spells and mental enhancements. Haste spells are also the domain of the enchanter, providing incredible boosts in attack speed for members of their group. Enchanters have many powers of illusion as well, allowing them to take the form of many different creatures and races. 
<br />

<br />
In battle, enchanters are able to bring order to chaotic situations, often saving their group in a fight that would otherwise be lost. Enchanters possess the ability to mesmerize their enemies, temporarily removing them from a battle. Attack slowing spells are also a specialty, dramatically lowering the speed of a monster's attacks for a period of time. In many situations, enchanters can call upon powerful charm spells to subjugate the mind of a monster and command it to do the enchanter's bidding. 
<br />

<br />
Enchanters are a powerful class, but often rely upon a group to reach their full potential. Experienced enchanters thrive in chaotic situations where they can make the most of their offensive abilities. The enchanter is a good choice for players who enjoy playing in groups and like to take charge of challenging situations. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Okay, let me start by saying I play all 16 classes, however my enchater is what for lack of a better word is called my "main".  Elemer was my first character and what was described as the class is why I bought the game back four years ago.  I am some what of a casual player, after 4 years elemer is only just now about to reach 60th level, he has however mastered or grandmastered most trade skills and has completed so may quests as to be an old hack and working out the bugs in the NPC text to get them to respond.
<br />

<br />
Okay lets start:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Enchanters are the most subtle of spell casters, with little focus on doing damage directly but tremendous impact on the world around them. Enchanters are primarily a magic-using class, with the ability to wear cloth armor and wield blunt weapons and daggers. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Fact; enchanters are for all intent worthless for direct DPS.  Add to that we basically run around in pajamas.  Our offense and defense skills max out before we hit 30th level.  By the time we are looking at the high end game it doesn't matter how great the dps of a staff is that we have, we'll never hit anything with it.  But that's okay, as : "Enchanters are the most subtle of spell casters...but tremendous impact on the world around them"
<br />

<br />
We don't effect things directly, we're ment to manipulate the circumstances of the event.
<br />

<br />
Only, in the last four expansions time and time again our abilities to effect the circumstances have been nerfed.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Enchanters specialize on improving the minds of their allies, with unmatched mana regeneration spells and mental enhancements. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
So many other classes have mana regen now, this is just plainly false.  And that's without even taking into account that from 45th to 59th no group wants enchanter mind buffs in group as KEI killed our use there.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Haste spells are also the domain of the enchanter, providing incredible boosts in attack speed for members of their group</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Okay second spell line mentioned in the write up, and it too is over shadowed by other classes.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Enchanters have many powers of illusion as well, allowing them to take the form of many different creatures and races. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Third item in the list.  Only all illusions are nerfed, and now several racial illusions are insanely hard to obtain.  And it's not like most illusions have any kind of real utility.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In battle, enchanters are able to bring order to chaotic situations, often saving their group in a fight that would otherwise be lost. Enchanters possess the ability to mesmerize their enemies, temporarily removing them from a battle. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Only starting with Velious (because SoE badly created the avatar script), all giants are un-mezzable.  This trend has been used to 'correct' anything SoE has made a mistake on.  The result being more often then not, when mezz really would "save thier group", enchanters find that all they have done is aggro an NPC that will kill them (remember the guy only wears pajamas) in three hits.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Attack slowing spells are also a specialty, dramatically lowering the speed of a monster's attacks for a period of time</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Okay, at least on Nameless, the trend is to look for a Shaman first, and an Enchanter only if no shaman are available for slowing.  Shaman as deamed to be better at it, they have good AC and HP, and better defense, the result is when they do pull agro for a slow, they live through it.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In many situations, enchanters can call upon powerful charm spells to subjugate the mind of a monster and command it to do the enchanter's bidding</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The reality is charm is and always has been only useful in carefully controlled situations.  If that weren't the fact then back when there was only the old world, everyone would have been playing an enchanter.
<br />

<br />
Now, with more and more creatures being given huge magic resists, and being flagged as uncharmable, lets face it, it's not just situational, it's pigeon holed out of usefulness entirely.
<br />

<br />
Let's remember, charm was the back up for mezz in situations were encounters had already been nerfed by the mobs being un-mezzable.
<br />

<br />
So this is in trueth a double nerf.
<br />

<br />
---------------------------------------------------------
<br />

<br />
Okay quick summary:
<br />

<br />
Enchanter crowd control is the combination of; stuns, mezzes, charms, and roots.
<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/eusa_wall.gif" alt="eusa_wall.gif" border="0" />   - Stun is nerfed.
<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/eusa_wall.gif" alt="eusa_wall.gif" border="0" />   - Mez is nerfed.
<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/eusa_wall.gif" alt="eusa_wall.gif" border="0" />   - Charm is nerfed.
<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/eusa_dance.gif" alt="eusa_dance.gif" border="0" />   * Root is left.  It's however as common as dirt in other classes.
<br />

<br />
Enchanter encounter manipulation is the combination of crowd contol (see above), group buffs, and NPC debuffs.
<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/eusa_wall.gif" alt="eusa_wall.gif" border="0" />   - Crowd control is nerfed.
<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/eusa_dance.gif" alt="eusa_dance.gif" border="0" />   - we have haste, but so do a lot of others and we're certainly not #1.
<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/eusa_dance.gif" alt="eusa_dance.gif" border="0" />   - we have slow, but so do a lot of others and we're certainly not #1.
<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/eusa_doh.gif" alt="eusa_doh.gif" border="0" />   - when exactly was the last time we used our other buffs?  i.e. Umbra?
<br />

<br />
Lastly as spell casters we are the only class were 100% of all our spells are magic based.  i.e. we have no poison, disease, cold or fire based spells, even in instances were our spells have poison counters to them and cause appropriate aggro, those spells are resisted vs magic resist.  In fact SoE's write up says:
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Enchanters are primarily a magic-using class</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
As of PoP, LoY, LDoN, and now GoD, the innate magic resistance of NPC's has sky rocketed.  They result being an implicate nerf of the entire class, not just individual spell lines.
<br />

<br />
Can anyone name any other class that has been subjected to this level of abuse?
<br />

<br />
Okay, /rant off
<br />

<br />
All I want know is this.  What is SoE's new vision of the class?  Because what they have written as of right now on thier own game description is 100% not what the class is.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />**************************************
<br />
"What?...Me?...Charm your wife???.....never!
<br />
**************************************</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
