                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The illusion nerf was a great upgrade.  I love being able to use air elemental, scaled wolf, WW, and NDT wherever I want.  Yes, we lost in a couple of areas.  The brownies thing is no big deal, as a vendor was added to HHK.  And we can't run around Velks non-KoS.  But the gain is much greater than the loss.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Only starting with Velious (because SoE badly created the avatar script), all giants are un-mezzable.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This started at launch, actually.  Fire Giants, Hill Giants, and Ice Giants, all not mezzable.  Neither were any dragons...all 2 of them.  Problem with SoV is that it was based around dragons and giants.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Okay, at least on Nameless, the trend is to look for a Shaman first, and an Enchanter only if no shaman are available for slowing. Shaman as deamed to be better at it, they have good AC and HP, and better defense, the result is when they do pull agro for a slow, they live through it.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I find it depends on the where.  For example, if landing slow quickly is important as are hps, but the area is likel to have single pulls, people prefer shamans.  If slow isn't important but nice to have, people prefer BLs for their DPS and mana regen buffs.  If CC is important, people want a chanter.  Each class has it's own strengths in addition to slow.  That is what determines who gets chosen.  And don't envy the shamans.  They get screwed in a lot of ways because of the power of their slow.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">So many other classes have mana regen now, this is just plainly false. And that's without even taking into account that from 45th to 59th no group wants enchanter mind buffs in group as KEI killed our use there. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
We are the masters of mana regen.  Bards do regen mana faster than us, but they can only do it for their group and the primary reason they are preferred for this role is because they stack with our buffs.  The rest were added because they needed to be.  The difference in RoK between having C2 or bard song and having nothing was huge.  It was the biggest part of what made enchanters a must have class.  It is also worth noting here that bards have always been able to grant greater mana regen than us.  It wasn't until I was level 27 that clarity was added to the game.  Anyway, I think the most telling point about this is the 45-59 thing.  Everyone has a KEI.  It's an assumed part of mana regen.  No other spell in the game is this way.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">when exactly was the last time we used our other buffs? i.e. Umbra?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
GRM and GoD!  And, uhm, NDT on pets?  Rune (regular, arcane is sort of a given).  I use Leviathian Eyes a lot and Wandering Mind is a quasi-buff.  I sometimes use WW for +attack, air elemental for lev, fire elemental for DS, illusion: &lt;good looking race&gt; for female ogres and trolls.  But really, how often does a cleric use buffs besides virtue/marzin, BoR, and BoV?  When it comes to lots of buffs, you can really just look to shamans and BLs.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I can't think of another class that has better hastes for their GROUP. Yes, some have self hastes, or pet hastes, but who has the best hastes in the game? If you can find a better haste than an enchanters, that can be cast on a group member, please tell me. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
He's talking about bards and overhaste.  A bard can sing a haste song (til epic procs) and then overhaste to exceed the cap.  We excel at putting people at the cap, but can't push them over.  Not something I worry about, really.  Our hastes rock, no complaints.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I think that marking certain mobs as unmezzable is a reasonable thing. This allows them to put a challenge back into an encounter that could be trivialized with mez. You need to create some different tactics for these encounters. And also, these are well known creatures. And you will learn quickly what things can and can't be mezzed. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Agree and disagree.  SoV, for example, was a PoS expansion because Mez wasn't usuable in all raid zones.  Can't mez giants, can't mez dragons, can't mez (well, can barely mez with rapture) insanely high MR dwarves.  This just wasn't fun, was poor design.  It wasn't use different tactics some of the time, it was don't mez.
<br />

<br />
And back to the original post:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Can anyone name any other class that has been subjected to this level of abuse?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Shamans.  A class based around slow and DoTs.  Their healing sucks because of it, compared to druids and clerics.  Their DPS sucks in short term fights.  Mind you, there are a lot of places they are great to have.  But there's more places where you'd rather have a BL.
<br />

<br />
The problem with shamans as well as ourselves is the power of what we do.  When I've got 5 mobs that hit for 900+ each mezzed...I add so much to the power of the party.  When a shaman reduces such a mob to 1/4th of it's DPS, the impact can similiarly huge.  Because of that, they feel the need to restrict us somehow.  Without doing that, everything would be easy with us, unless they make things hard, in which case people must have us.
<br />

<br />
The truth is, if it wasn't for the duration of KEI, people would take us for haste and mana regen alone.  That's how it was in SoV.  It just sucks for us because being a buff whore is boring;)</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
