I cannot disagree more.  We lost a lot.  Part of the loss is the general dumbing down of EQ.  What we lost was our sense of faction.  The old school enchanters <span style="font-weight: bold">knew</span> faction.  If people in my guild wanted to know about faction, they knew to ask an enchanter (and, to some extent a bard).  Of course, faction was mortally wounded with Luclin and finally killed with PoP.  It was a rite of passage to get your mana vial spells from the brownies, and I still fondly recall the sheer terror of that 15 minute trip from Felwithe.
<br />

<br />
For the most part, charm was a crowd control mechanism.  I learned charming while fighting Forest Giants in Frontier Mountain -- as crowd control.  When I felt comfortable with it, I explored its use as a method for adding DPS to a group, and eventually soloing in Overthere.  It would appear that we learned too well.
<br />

